The first virtual operator is coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer almost all the services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not gonna take long to get there.
That Czech operators are one of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it in mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed this by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) who warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of regulating roaming rates, it is likely that a paradoxical situation will be reached - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS sending from abroad will be cheaper than if sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, has already stated that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operators.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant price decrease to which classic operators should also react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can be successful.
On the other hand, there is no need to look too far for examples.
In February this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator was able to obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking there is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on many more specific target groups.
In addition, for them to function effectively, it is enough for them with many fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled at low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that however, often contradicts the offer of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half of the cost with respect to competition.
However, as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland can also be a good blow to bet for a trivial goal group.
This operator is specifically addressed to the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - he's the operator who likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether it seems as if the concept of Poland could catch up with us in our country.
This is why Vodafone's spokesperson, Miroslav Čepický: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover from the point of view of the supply of services is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there are any virtual operators in the Czech Republic, that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech R. does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," said in telephone conversation for mobile.cz, Jana Studničková, spokesman for the Penta financial group.
Indirectly it ensured that current mobile telephony operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows the group GTS Novera that I would like to take a step forward to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephone services but also mobile phones.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have been able to make progress at the meetings," said the spokesperson for the group, Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe they're flashing better times.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At present we believe that the situation is suitable for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
To date no one has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this field," he said for mobile.cz, Vladimil Sršeň, spokesperson for Telephone O2.
Other operators are concerned with the specificity of the Czech market.
The spokesperson for T-mobile, Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2's opinion, adds: "We have not yet registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
And add: "In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator by the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table a specific contract that could be studied in such a short horizon"
Vodafone directs its attention rather to meeting the requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this with regard to the distribution of expenditure and infrastructure.
Precisely we consider it to be the biggest contribution from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on the mobile."
Responsible offices - with operators and meat
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a price drop and thus a decrease in profits.
Then why facilitate entry into competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull out of the same rope, proof of that is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure to the ČTU was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile society.
This is attested to by the public information available on the websites of ČTÚ.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: "Also, the competitive environment in the mobile telephony market has not long been open to a fourth operator.
With regard to the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that another player's entry into the market would mean for him and, above all, for his major services requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging because of the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (UOHS).
However, this expressed its typical position in the face of this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile phone operator and a virtual operator was concluded.
To date no agreement has been closed since the offer of potential stakeholders was not sufficiently interesting for classic operators," added our question Kristian Chalupa, from the UOHS Department of External Relations.
These statements did not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices that must represent the interests of consumers, it is more than a consideration, apart from that they must note that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In abroad where virtual operators work normally we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to the price drop of mobile telephony services"
Obviously, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market media and the fall in prices do not fall within the interest of the UOHS.
The truly shocking thing in all this case lies in the dissonant reactions resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is an accident is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no sign of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore, they do not have a corresponding rise in liability in their market actions.
The tools needed to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunication regulators," added Chalupa's response.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is obviously a relevant market analysis developed by ČTU that telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile telephony operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of his network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must be necessarily dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for UOHS should be a warning that three mobile operators are going up in a similar manner.
Current complaints from stakeholders (induced by the so-called GTS Novera company) show that in all negotiations with operators they are shocked with many similar impediments.
Loading responsibility in the ČTU is a rather common trick in the field of telecommunications from which UOHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We've met with him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately a new amendment to the telecommunications law was introduced recently for the extension of the competition of ČTU in the field of commercial tenders that had not been put into effect, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This should be well known by UOHS representatives, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one looks
At the same time, it is unconsciously still working as well as a pseudovirtual operator that in the Czech mobile telephone networks there are a few already.
They are companies that put their own prices to mobile telephony services which, however, only a part are public.
These are usually companies dedicated to multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a few chosen people get the list of prices of these companies.
The magic is in which the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the company in charge of a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will receive after special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile telephony operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as those cited could be considered infringements in terms of contract terms that could be translated at the end of collaboration with the given society," he answered the question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
Exactly in the case of the three companies mentioned above, they may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they get no negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are only used by such a despicable percentage of customers.
These must also accept that the SIM card of your phone is not in your name so you cannot have it as a normal customer of operators."
Precisely this is what should seem to the least strange ČTU.
In addition, there is a new question for UOHS.
If mobile telephony operators surround their eyes in this type of procedure, why are they blocking the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it should not be content with the operators' explanations that they have no idea of this history and that their trading conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market resulted in a significant decrease in service prices.
At the same time, practically in all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, classic operators tried to protect themselves from this eruption.
The arguments used by these were almost all identical - too small, a market, eventually too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases have defended operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure, they made the first virtual operator appear and others began to emerge with it.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body goes through this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience, we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of the powers in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this information between backstages is correct and the virtual operator actually arrives at these lands, then the Czech market of mobile telephony is likely to start moving again.
If any of the operators allows any virtual mobile telephony operator to enter, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the Czech official anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the hymn Where, my home.
The new anthem was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one male voice and one female voice, one with Choir and another instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka are responsible for this.
The authors of the hymn arrangements are Otakar Jeremias and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to the four versions.
Bělohlávek views this Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio has already said before it intentionally chose for the Singing solos with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried with both of them and then, also, with the Choir that were fixed in the dictionary so that the text would be well understood, so that it would have consonance," he said.
The Czech official anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home rang for the first time in 1834 in the State Theatre tables in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it their own.
The first stanza of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 was naturally made part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
