The MHD in Prague takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, is written in the history of the Prague Transportation Company the date on which the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic bonus in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can now be purchased by nearly 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy the 30-day, 90-day bonus and the annual (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and load it simultaneously on their chip card at the infocentres and posts of the transport company at the Metro stations, Museum, Mŏstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Bonuses can already be purchased on the Internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, up to the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget about ticket sales at subway stations, where until now they had to regularly queue to get a regular ticket out.
The bonus is purchased online, and the Opencard card is recharged to you in one of the 13 branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is a window available to passengers with prepared staff who assists stakeholders with the purchase on the internet and also with the reloading of the bonus purchased on their card," said the project's spokesperson, Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to recharge the electronic bonus on the Opencard on the automatic expensive machines found in some subway halls.
How are these expensive machines?
They are red, they remind us of a ticketing machine and travelers will probably have already fixed themselves in them at the stations of the Roztyly Metro, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five in the city but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný completed.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Simply enter the Opencard chip card and the previously paid bonus will be loaded only on it.
Electronic bonuses from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, in the roundabout trains and bus lines from numbers 300 to 499 that mainly use the inhabitants of the towns of central Bohemia.
"On trains dedicated to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reader card that will help confirm the validity of the time and zone of the bonus", explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drapal of the organization Ropid that sets the schedules of the collective transport of Prague.
The circumvalition buses have their reading cards mounted on the driver's locker.
When entering, it is necessary not only to show the driver's card but also to accompany the driver with the Opencard at the place intended for it on the side of the box.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the bond.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonuses there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drapal added.
Passengers who don't travel on the circumvaliation buses and don't remember when the bonus's validity is finished can go to the expensive machines where the cards are reloaded.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown information on the validity of your document.
