Repeated drivers due to alcoholemia must install the alcohol alcohol
Interior wants the driver with three administrative sanctions for alcoholemia, to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the start of the drunk vehicle, or if it does not blow.
The initiative was announced last June and is now included in the annual memory of the State Attorney General ' s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last for a year.
Its purpose is the reinstatement of the driver, so it will also receive a course of road re-education.
In addition to the Office of the Attorney-General for Road Safety, the Directorate-General for Traffic (DGT) and the Fundación Instituto Tecnológico para la Seguridad del Auto (FITSA) will participate in the experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 per cent of motorists reported more than once by driving drunks return to the car.
Alcohol would prevent it as it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the rate of alcohol in the air inhaled and prevents the start of the car if the driver does not blow abate; or when an alcohol concentration is detected it is higher than the permitted one.
Its cost is higher than 1000 euros and would run on behalf of the sanctioned person.
In this regard, a study carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with these devices reduce infringements by up to 65% during the first year of deployment.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save 115 people's lives each year.
The measure refers to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address such behaviour before they result in criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by regular means, and yet the necessary criminal reform requires reform in an organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial fashion, although it has already been experimentally implemented in some industrial and public service vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative by the PSOE in which it intends to install this system in school buses, as has been done in France.
