They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (sleeping) or sleepwalking, but it doesn't have to be that way.
As we have already mentioned, they may also be associated with very high fever rates, stress situations or overexcitation.
However, it is a phenomenon that has not been studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
You may speak in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a whisper or anything else (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where the demonstration is very intense, it would be useful to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to see if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him the way out.
We said it is a benign alteration, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another disturbance of the dream that can be treated (e.g. if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to bed.
So look for quiet games and avoid television programs or series that are afraid or a little violent.
With very nervous children and a great deal of relaxation, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will help the child to have a calmer dream.
Once the dreams appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day you won't remember anything about what's happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his dream.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you are feeling very distressed during several episodes, you should consult or find out what is causing such anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common), do not fall into the temptation to interrogate him to hear information from him.
You won't get anything, because when you're asleep, you're not aware of how to organize your thinking.
You will also hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming of saying that, so be careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to know his secrets.
Not even kidding.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
