The interview - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated his 10th anniversary of his foundation yesterday, and his president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Hema-Québec has again been one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, he regained the confidence of the public that had been seriously shaken by the blood scandal contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which intended to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster could no longer be reproduced.
While Judge Krever was late in presenting his relationship, some provinces then established a committee that aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this mission.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
" In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of the people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and much work during the years that followed, we have regained the confidence of the public ", he says before proudly affirming that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that "trust is extremely fragile."
Since its inception, on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we attended in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
So we rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know it and when a serious disease can emanate from it, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But a few years ago, it has been shown beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleid acid tests that allow the presence of the virus in donors directly in the blood of donors, not those of anti-virus antibodies, on which the tests used so far were based.
Tests of nucleide acid allowed shortening the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We could reduce this period for less than a week.
We thus substantially reduced the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of contracting AIDS due to blood transfusion.
Nowadays, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"That means you will have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood products each year, it will pass more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I believe that you can now receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover your health without concern," says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
" Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Meeting, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
You must be constantly vigilant ", pursue Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Québec must also provide adequate supplies.
" Needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
Since the most aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the network of blood donors that regroups on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All people with good health, 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria, however, can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 % of the people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory covering the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But the members of this donor network must be renewed as they age and cannot donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since today's life is very wild, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate your blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye balloons and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered as biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
" We held a few weeks ago, the bank of our thousandth sample of blood from the umbilical cord and it is expected to take more than a thousand of these out of the year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year," said Dr. Décary who describes this cord blood-taking program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this " since Hema-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program at all hospitals in Quebec.
