Overlapping psychology: Why spend more money?
The auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological bases - economics of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to the study in Science magazine, people do not want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists have tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One of the groups of volunteers played lottery, the other participated in a auction and was being examined through the functional magnetic resonance imaging system (fMRI) the active brain areas of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could earn money, but during auctions, where it is fundamental element to bet more than the other, by losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called stratum located below the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "auto prize" of the nervous system.
According to scientists, increased betting is explained as a prevention not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate his theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups waged against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product concerned, and its members betted.
In addition, another group was promised that if they win, they would receive $15 more prize.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case the auction was lost, even that money was lost.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the group playing "against failure" were willing to wager even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be deducted from any previously existing economic theory.
For those so far explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only the visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation" - established Andrew Schotter, professor of the University of New York's economic faculty.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
Around the world some five hundred million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated because many of the sick do not know they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses dependent on the pathogen are spread through two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other blood and body humor viruses (sperm, vagina humor, saliva).
It is recommended that travellers be protected by vaccine against virus A and B, against C there are no vaccines.
Hepatitis A symptoms appear two or three weeks after eating the infected food, manifested by a general poor condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this appear in the skin and white of the eyes jaundice, excrement becomes clear, dark urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year one million people die in cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected is treated pharmacologically.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Premature recognition, systematic medical control is therefore very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are now about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
Since this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease has healing if it is discovered in time, it is possible to eliminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
On 30 September, World Hepatitis Day was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its objective is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and to the importance of their early recognition.
Does it hurt less who they believe in God?
According to a recent investigation, religious faith has a soothing effect that also alleviates the death of martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at Oxford University carried out an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in how it influences human pain - reported the British Telegraph newspaper.
Within the framework of this unique experiment, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists applied electric shock, while everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the scanning technique of the human brain, it was found that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in the series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the various departments of the University are also involved.
The analysis occurred in the following way; they set a sparkly instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their eyes on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, work of 17th century Sassoferrato and the Lady of Armamin by Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would cause a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts during that period while observing the painting of religious theme or the other.
Catholics said that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "they calmed down and in their hearts peace reigned."
By looking at the religious background, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they saw Leonardo’s work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image that is so striking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists as well, you only have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person who feels very positively, as if by a mother or father," said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright celebrated the result of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases truly change our personality" - Wright added.
After these formidable results there is only one question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of her size were shown to the faithful?
Would the vision of a high quality Virgin Mary bring even better results?
