The intelligent car imitates the flight of the honeybee
What would be the best way to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of existing obstacle sensors in nature?
For example, the beekeepers.
In a surprising project presented at the Japan CEATEC, the beekeepers provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the system of robotic driving cars type BR23C imitator of nature, which gave it the characteristics of beejors, with the ultimate objective of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight each honeybee creates its own particular ovated space that actually looks a lot like our safe capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role in the composite eyes of beeches that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eyes, engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the beeches, modifies the direction by turning to the necessary extent the wheels.
Unlike any current system, this maneuver is completely instinctive.
"If not, the robot of the vehicle could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety-protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other beepers.
This process must be carried out in an open and close eyes.
However, unlike beejors, the movement cannot move upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the steering direction of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for beekeepers to avoid other beeches, here only used as a possibility for the auto robot the rotating movement and acceleration also the braking.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is greater, which means that they have a longer life span than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is instinctive and intelligent reaction, not data processing capacity, nor much less storage capacity.
This device in each second must only process some input signals and react as appropriate.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabyte memories, or megabytes.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which, according to Nissan calculations, can be incorporated into the models manufactured in series within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding the obstacles that exist on his way.
