Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, national industrial selling prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month’s prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimum, with 0.1 per cent.
Internal sales prices in the processing industry have increased at least by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
The higher price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector ( 2.8 per cent), due firstly to the increase of 4.6 per cent per month in bags and belts and the increase of 2.5 per cent in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in chemical material production industry prices (1.6 per cent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector (1.4 per cent), in the production of electric machinery and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the processing sectors of wood (0.1 per cent).
They did not change the prices of paper manufacturing, publishing and printing.
In the rest of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, primarily as a result of the increase in official prices from 1 July.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the highest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4%).
In the metal processing sector there was an increase of 13.2 per cent, while in the food, drink and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally increased prices by 10.2 percent.
The prices of electricity, gas, heat and water exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 per cent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the highest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in energy and intermediate sector prices there was no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the highest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
In the branches producing consumer goods a decrease of 6.8 per cent and in investment goods 1.4 per cent was recorded.
The export prices of the industry calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 per cent.
The contribution of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro and by 7.1 per cent compared to the dollar, compared to August 2007 strengthened by 7.5 per cent compared to the euro and 15.9 per cent compared to the dollar.
