The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore photograph effectively what is happening in the large Italian urban centers and also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, which with the birth of the great methics on the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
Almost always disappearing are historical places, full of memory, "it's as if a friend died, a acquaintance with whom a piece of place was shared and so much emotion," observes the director of the new movie Paradise, the film that 20 years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury in Cannes, which counted the poetry of a provincial cinema room and the nostalgia for the way to live the film that may be lost forever.
The figures given by the Anec, the main trader association, speak clearly: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have been closed, and paying for most are mostly the rooms of the main cities: 10 minus in Florence, 9 minus in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 minus in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures are as first, Emilia-Romaña with 82 less cinemas, following Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the responsible for its disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these three Italian regions have recorded the largest number of new methic cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 is in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romaña.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally" observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to ensure the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to transfer themselves to the meticians.
Not to mention the lack of funds for traders: the previous debt of the state is approximately EUR 10 million.
It is shameful from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
In order to sustain the sector it would serve between 16 and 18 million euros per year".
Interesting to the case of Bologna, the first Italian city concerned by the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first such in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono room is in the historical center that in the periphery.
The proposed rules include means of tax facilitation for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators may enter the restricted traffic area and will have special parking rates.
"It's an initiative I like" observes Giuseppe Tornatore" and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is true that in order to contrast the extra power of the meticones, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that was always important to me: the closing of the cinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to realize the "New Paradise Cinema", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass before the Rialto or the Quirinale of the already closed National Road, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the signs blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side".
